    "body": "### Problem\n\n`vim.treesitter.stop()` *stops treesitter highlighting for a buffer*, but it also has the unexpected side-effect of turning off language injections.\n\n\n\n\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n1. Set Neovim up to use the following minimal `init.lua`:\n    ``` lua\n    -----------------------\n    -- Set up treesitter --\n    -----------------------\n    require(\"nvim-treesitter.configs\").setup({\n        ensure_installed = { \"lua\", \"markdown\" },\n        auto_install = true,\n        highlight = { enable = true },\n        incremental_selection = {\n            enable = true,\n            keymaps = {\n                init_selection = \"tis\",\n                node_incremental = \"ni\",\n            },\n        },\n    })\n    \n    \n    -----------------------------------------------------------------\n    -- Turn off treesitter highlighting whenever we enter a buffer --\n    -----------------------------------------------------------------\n    vim.api.nvim_create_autocmd(\"BufEnter\", {\n        group = vim.api.nvim_create_augroup(\"test\", {}),\n        callback = function() vim.treesitter.stop() end\n    })\n    ```\n\n1. Create a file `test.md` with the following text:\n     ````` markdown\n     ``` lua\n     local foo = {\n       123,\n       \"hello \" .. \"world!\"\n     }\n     ```\n     `````\n3. Try using incremental selection within the Lua block (`tis` with the cursor inside the code block). You'll see that regardless of where the cursor is placed, the whole Lua block will be selected.\n4. Now, try the same after editing `init.lua` to remove the final autocommand. The highlighting will be different as expected, but you'll now also see that incremental selection takes Lua syntax into account.\n\nYou can see a similar effect in a normal Lua file, e.g. by trying incremental selection within something like `vim.cmd[[ echo 'hello' 'world!' ]]`.\n\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nI would expect incremental selection, and indeed the whole syntax tree for a buffer, to be unaffected by turning treesitter highlighting off/on. In particular, I would expect language injections to work in the same way regardless of whether highlighting is enabled.\n\nThat said, now that I understand why this issue is happening I wonder if this is actually intended behaviour. If so, I think it would be worth mentioning in the docs that `vim.treesitter.start|stop()` affect more than just the visual aspect of highlighting. \n\n#### Workaround\nPossibly worth noting that a hacky workaround is to simply shim `for_each_highlight_state()` with an empty function like so:\n\n``` Lua\nfor _, buf in ipairs(vim.api.nvim_list_bufs()) do\n  pcall(function()\n    local highlighter = vim.treesitter.highlighter.active[buf]\n    ---@diagnostic disable-next-line: duplicate-set-field\n    function highlighter:for_each_highlight_state() end\n  end)\nend\n```\n\nThis removes treesitter highlighting without affecting the syntax tree.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\n0.10.2\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nN/A; this is a treesitter issue\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nmacOS 14.6.1\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nghostty/1.0.1\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-256color\n\n### Installation\n\nhomebrew",
